      <section id="uid2">
        <title>Differences between Mass and Weight</title>
        <para id="id63434">Mass is measured in kilograms (kg) and is the amount of matter in an object. An object's mass does not change unless matter is added or removed from the object.</para>
        <para id="id63439">The differences between mass and weight can be summarised in the following table:</para>
        <table id="id63443" summary="">
          <tgroup cols="2">
            <tbody>
              <row>
                <entry>
                  <emphasis effect="bold">Mass</emphasis>
                </entry>
                <entry>
                  <emphasis effect="bold">Weight</emphasis>
                </entry>
              </row>
              <row>
                <entry>1. is a measure of how much matter there is in an object.</entry>
                <entry>1. is the force with which the Earth attracts an object.</entry>
              </row>
              <row>
                <entry>2. is measured in kilograms.</entry>
                <entry>2. is measured in newtons</entry>
              </row>
              <row>
                <entry>3. is the same on any planet.</entry>
                <entry>3. is different on different planets.</entry>
              </row>
              <row>
                <entry>4. is a scalar.</entry>
                <entry>4. is a vector.</entry>
              </row>
            </tbody>
          </tgroup>
        </table>
